        <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¬ Uganda deploys troops to DR Congo to repel militias</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            Uganda is deploying troops to eastern DRC to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-02-2025-r1-1-combat-militias-accused-of-committing-massacres?source=website" target="_blank">combat militias accused of committing massacres</a>. Ugandan forces, already in Ituri province, are working with DRC troops against the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF), linked to the Islamic State. Meanwhile, the M23 rebel group, backed by Rwanda, has seized Goma and Bukavu, threatening Butembo. Ugandaâ€™s army chief issued a 24-hour ultimatum for rebels in Bunia to surrender. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            The UN accuses M23 of executing children and attacking hospitals. UN agencies have previously accused both the rebels and Congolese government forces of recruiting children.  Burundi is withdrawing its troops, raising concerns about Congoâ€™s stability. With over 100 armed groups fighting for mineral-rich territory, fears of DRCâ€™s fragmentation are growing. 
          </p>
          </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡®ðŸ‡· British couple in Iran faces espionage accusation</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Iran has accused British nationals Craig and Lindsay Foreman of espionage. The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-02-2025-r2-2-couple-was-detained-in-January?source=website" target="_blank">couple was detained in January</a> while traveling through Kerman on a global motorcycle journey. Iranâ€™s judiciary says they gathered intelligence in multiple provinces and had ties to hostile intelligence agencies. Their families dismissed the charges as baseless, while the UK Foreign Office expressed deep concern and provided consular assistance. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Iran has a history of detaining Western nationals, often accused of using them as leverage in negotiations. The couple ignored previous warnings about visiting Iran and believed in global goodwill. Last week, the British ambassador met them in Kerman, though Iran denies allegations of politically motivated detentions. 
          </p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¸ Russia and US eye joint Arctic energy projects after Saudi talks </strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            While much of the focus has been on the Russia-Ukraine war negotiations, the US and Russia held bilateral talks. Kirill Dmitriev, head of the Russian Direct Investment Fund, said they discussed <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-02-2025-r3-3-potential-cooperation-on-arctic-energy-projects?source=website" target="_blank">potential cooperation on Arctic energy projects</a> during a meeting in Saudi Arabia. While the talks were broad, both sides explored specific areas of collaboration. 
          </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
           This comes at a time when Arctic geopolitics has been a central focal point. Trump has previously expressed interest in acquiring Greenland and seeks to expand US influence in the Arctic. Despite ExxonMobilâ€™s 2018 withdrawal from Arctic projects due to sanctions, Russia is pushing for renewed investment. The talks may pave the way for future joint ventures in Greenland with the US and Russia, which could further alarm European allies.
          </p>
          </mj-text>
