          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">Will Ukraine and Russia draw the line?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">This weekâ€™s competing summits (Russia's discussions on Ukraine and Europeâ€™s talks on Ukraine's security) highlight a shared desire to end the war. However, they hold significantly different views on key issues determining a peace agreement. A major point of contention is Ukraine's potential NATO membership.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">President Zelenskyy <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-02-2025-bq1-4-would-likely-consider-border-concessions?source=website" target="_blank">would likely consider border concessions</a> if Ukraine received NATO guarantees. Russia opposes this, arguing that NATO expansion was a primary trigger for the war. Russian FM Sergey Lavrov has stated that Ukraine can join the EU but not NATO. Ukraine, however, aims to join both NATO and the EU, but it must meet specific criteria and cannot be accelerated, leading to divided opinions among NATO members.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">Russia professes to protect ethnic Russians in Eastern Ukraine, citing referendums that show overwhelming support for joining Russia, though these referendums were conducted under dubious conditions. A proper and monitored referendum would be necessary in the annexed areas for any agreement on borders. If Russia accepts such a situation, it may face similar demands for regions like Chechnya or places in the East where non-ethnic Russians are discontent with the war.</p>
        </mj-text>
